				</div>
<div class="w480"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/27/opinion/2272014min/2272014min-blog480.jpg" id="100000002738853" width="480" height="298" alt="Harry Reid on Feb. 25, 2014." /><span class="credit">J. Scott Applewhite/Associated Press</span><span class="caption">Harry Reid on Feb. 25, 2014.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid decided to postpone a vote on raising the minimum wage, in part, it appears, because he does not have enough Democratic support to pass the measure. The holdouts include several Democratic senators from low-wage and mostly southern states who are up for reelection this year. That is pathetic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A higher minimum wage is a basic response to the low and stagnating wages that have long afflicted most Americans. It is not a cure-all, it is not new or visionary. It is a time-tested step in the direction of higher living standards, broader prosperity and a more stable economy.<br />
<span id="more-16265"></span><br />
If it is difficult to corral even Democrats in favor of what is by all measures a <a href="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/18/the-minimum-minimum-wage/">modest increase</a> &#8212; from $7.25 an hour, its level since 2009, to $10.10 an hour by 2016 &#8212; what chance is there going forward for innovative and comprehensive policies and programs to address the nationâs economic challenges?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some Democrats reportedly went weak kneed on the minimum wage following a report from the Congressional Budget Office which estimated that raising the wage to $10.10 could lead to the loss of 500,000 jobs over the next three years.Â That conclusion, however, is easily rebuttable, as explained in a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/20/opinion/the-clear-benefits-of-a-higher-wage.html?ref=editorials">recent editorial</a>. A policymaker who would be dissuaded by the C.B.O. report was probably not serious about raising the minimum in the first place.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other Democrats seem to think Â that $10.10 an hour is too high, even though it is low by relevant economic benchmarks and historical comparisons. One argument isÂ that $9 an hour would be better, because a single parent with two children making $9 an hour would qualify for tax credits boosting yearly pay to around $25,500. That ignores the fact that childless workers doÂ not qualify for the tax credits. It also ignores that low wages are often coupled with part-time hours, such that theoretical calculations of the available tax credits often do not pan out in reality.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Worse, it ignores that many of the nationâs low-wage employers are big and profitable corporations. The legitimate purpose of low-earner tax credits is to encourage low-wage workers to stay employed. The purpose is not to allow profitable companies to pay employees poorly &#8212; and executives and shareholders lavishly &#8212; while relying on taxpayers to keep the employees out of poverty.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Groups that support a higher minimum wage are making the best of the Senate delay by using the time to build more grassroots support and to lobby lawmakers. Given Democratsâ demonstrated penchant for advancing Republican arguments, they have their work cut out for them.</p>
	</div>
